{
  "texts": [
    "Body painting: Another potent visual signal comes from the use of color.",
    "Humans naturally change the color of their faces and upper body when offended or angry (blushing), and usually they turn redthe most aposematic color (Harvey and Paxton, 1981; Crozier, 2010).",
    "Apart from this legacy of biological evolution, humans also have a legacy of early cultural evolution for employing more drastic colors via body painting.",
    "The beginnings of body painting go much deeper than any rock painting and most likely originated at least with the oldest use of various pigments (Mithen, 2005; Roebroeks et al., 2012).",
    "No human culture is known to be totally free of body painting."
  ]
}